give the earth a break from from drilling, fracking, mining & clear cutting, employ tons of people to collect and sort it; utilize bioremediation wherever possible. choose processes that are the least ecologically destructive to break materials down into their constituent forms, utilize the research that has been ongoing for decades but underutilized because it was "cheaper" to just keep pulling stuff out of the ground.

if we view our planet as a closed system with finite ability to rebound from the dearth of our consumption and the cancer of our convenience we may recognize the responsibility we all must share.

snippet.textDisplay:
Trash isn't useless and it isn't valueless.  The current problem is that most of it isn't valuable enough to recover.  This is changing.  For example, methane gas is mined from some garbage tips. Chemists have recently worked out a way to turn plastics back into a recycled crude oil.

Even if it were practical to send trash off-planet, we shouldn't be doing it.  It will become more valuable as mining and food resources are depleted.  Emerging technology will make resource recovery cheaper and cleaner.  At some point, it will become economical to process a vast array of trash from garbage tips and turn it into a wide variety of new resources.

snippet.textDisplay:
There is another obvious reason: We lose resources. Everything we throw away was biomatter, hydrocarbons, rare earths, gold, other metals etc. which are finite on this planet. Getting them back from asteroids is also very costly.
The best thing we could do is to research efficient recycling technologies.
Let nanobots take the trash apart into their different molecules or atoms or continue researching plastic eating bacteria.
Lunching garbage into space is Futurama-level stupidity.
